Data Binding in Angular represents the communication between a component and the
DOM. It ensures that the model and view are synchronized. Angular offers
different types of data binding to cater to varied application requirements.


KEY TYPES OF DATA BINDING

 1. One-Way Data Binding

    * Data flows in a single direction from the component to the DOM or vice
      versa.
    * Example: Interpolation, Property Binding, Event Binding.

 2. Two-Way Data Binding

    * Enables bi-directional data flow, offering real-time synchronization
      between the component and the DOM.
    * Syntax: Utilize [(ngModel)] or [( )] for attribute binding. [(ngModel)] is
      specifically designed for forms, necessitating the FormsModule for
      integration.

 3. One-Way from Source
    One-way binding ensures that changes in the source will dictate whether the
    destination in the DOM is updated or not.

    * Example: Style or Attribute Binding.

 4. One-Time Binding

    One-time binding involves a single transfer of data from source to target
    without ongoing synchronization. This is useful when the data doesn't change
    and you don't want the overhead of continuous checks.

    * For Efficiency: Use in scenarios with data that's static or changes
      infrequently.


BEST PRACTICES FOR DATA BINDING

 * Simplicity Breeds Clarity: Limit two-way and one-time bindings to clear and
   justified contexts.

 * Temporal Precision: Use one-time bindings when data is static.

 * Systematic Updates: Employ strategies that maintain data integrity, such as
   ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush, and manually triggering ChangeDetectorRef.

 * Performance Considerations: Understand the potential performance implications
   of each data binding type and use them judiciously.


CODE EXAMPLE: TYPES OF DATA BINDING

Here is the TypeScript code:

import { Component, ChangeDetectionStrategy, ChangeDetectorRef } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
export class AppComponent {
  public message = "Initial message";
  public btnContent = "Disable";

  constructor(private cdr: ChangeDetectorRef) {}

  updateMessage() {
    this.message = new Date().toTimeString();
    // Manually trigger Change Detection
    this.cdr.detectChanges();
  }

  toggleBtn() {
    this.btnContent = this.btnContent === "Disable" ? "Enable" : "Disable";
  }
}

Services are instrumental in Angular for finer architectural design and sharing
common functionality across components.

Angular automatically injects a service when a component or another service
needs it. This mechanism fosters the "Don't Repeat Yourself" (DRY) principle,
leading to more modular, maintainable, and testable code.


SERVICE CREATION

You can create a service in Angular using either of these methods:

 1. CLI: Use the Angular CLI to generate a service.

    ng generate service my-service


 2. Manual: Create a .ts file for the service and define the class.


USING THE SERVICE

 1. Service Registration:

    * Module: Link the service to a specific module by adding it to the
      providers array in @NgModule.

    @NgModule({
      declarations: [
        MyComponent
      ],
      providers: [MyService],
      imports: [CommonModule]
    })


    * Dependency Injection Tree: Use a tree level below the root or at a
      component level.

    @Injectable({
      providedIn: 'root'
    })


 2. Dependency Injection:

Annotate the constructor in the component or service to be injected.

constructor(private myService: MyService) {}


 3. Lifecycle Management: Handle service lifecycle based on the specific
    requirements, such as persistent state management.


CODE EXAMPLE: SERVICE

Here is the TypeScript code:

// service.ts
@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class MyService {
  private data: any;

  setData(data: any): void {
    this.data = data;
  }

  getData(): any {
    return this.data;
  }
}

// component.ts
export class MyComponent {
  constructor(private myService: MyService) {}

  saveDataLocally(data: any): void {
    this.myService.setData(data);
  }

  fetchStoredData(): any {
    return this.myService.getData();
  }
}


In this case, the MyService will persist its data property throughout its
lifetime, and any component or service can access or modify it using the defined
methods.

Dependency Injection (DI) is a core concept in Angular, where components (or
services) depend on other components. Angular handles the creation and
management of these dependencies.


SIMPLIFIED EXPLANATION

DI takes three steps:

 1. Registration: Identify the components to be injected.
 2. Resolution: Find the appropriate dependencies.
 3. Injection: Insert the resolved dependencies.


KEY ANGULAR FEATURES LINKED TO DI

 * Modules: Angular applications are made up of modules, each with its
   dependency injector.
 * Providers: Within modules, providers offer a mechanism for registering
   dependencies.


CODE EXAMPLE: DI IN ANGULAR

Here is the Angular code:

// Service definition
@Injectable()
export class DataService {
  getData() {
    return "Some data";
  }
}

// Register in a module
@NgModule({
  providers: [DataService],
  // ...
})
export class MyModule {}

// Constructor injection in a component
@Component({
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {
  constructor(private dataService: DataService) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    console.log(this.dataService.getData());
  }
}

Handling events in Angular involves capturing and responding to user or system
actions. Angular provides declarative and imperative methods to accomplish this.


DECLARATIVE APPROACH

Declarative methods involve writing event handlers directly in the Angular
template using event binding.

SYNTAX

For event binding, Angular uses (event) syntax to listen for DOM events and
execute an associated method in the component.

(e.g.) Click Event:

 * Template:

   <button (click)="onClick($event)">Click Me</button>


 * Component:

   onClick(event: MouseEvent): void {
       console.log('Button was clicked', event);
   }


(e.g.) Input Event:

 * Template:

   <input (input)="onInput($event)">


 * Component:

   onInput(event: Event): void {
       const inputText = (event.target as HTMLInputElement).value;
       console.log('Input value changed:', inputText);
   }


Event Objects are optionally passed to event handling functions. These objects
contain specific properties based on the event type, such as MouseEvent for
click events and KeyboardEvent for keyboard-related ones.


IMPERATIVE APPROACH

While Angular promotes a declarative style, it also supports an imperative one,
where event listeners are manually added and removed through the @ViewChild
decorator of TypeScript.

SYNTAX

 * HTML Template:

   <div #targetDiv>Target DIV</div>


 * Component Class:

   @ViewChild('targetDiv') targetDiv: ElementRef;

   ngAfterViewInit(): void {
     this.targetDiv.nativeElement.addEventListener('click', this.onClick);
   }

   ngOnDestroy(): void {
     this.targetDiv.nativeElement.removeEventListener('click', this.onClick);
   }

   onClick(event: MouseEvent): void {
     console.log('Div clicked:', event);
   }


In this method, the ngAfterViewInit method sets up the event listener, and the
ngOnDestroy method removes it to prevent memory leaks or unexpected behavior.

Two-way binding in Angular synchronizes data between the data model and the view
in both directions. Any changes in the data model automatically reflect in the
view and vice versa.


IMPLEMENTATION IN ANGULAR

Angular primarily uses two-way binding through the [(ngModel)] directive,
leveraging the FormsModule or ReactiveFormsModule.


USING [(NGMODEL)] AND FORMSMODULE

 1. Module Setup: Import the FormsModule in your Angular module.

    import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

    @NgModule({
        imports: [FormsModule],
        // ...
    })
    export class AppModule { }


 2. Input Binding: Use [(ngModel)] in the view to enable two-way binding with an
    input element.

    <input [(ngModel)]="name" name="name" />


 3. Data Model: Define the associated property in the component.

    @Component({...})
    export class TwoWayBindingComponent {
        public name: string;
    }


This setup ensures that any changes to the input element are reflected in the
name property and vice versa.


USING [(NGMODEL)] WITH REACTIVEFORMSMODULE

If you choose to integrate [(ngModel)] with ReactiveFormsModule, follow these
steps:

 1. Module Setup: Import the ReactiveFormsModule in your Angular module.

    * Code Example: app.module.ts

    import { ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

    @NgModule({
        imports: [ReactiveFormsModule],
        // ...
    })
    export class AppModule { }


 2. FormGroup Creation: Create an Angular FormGroup and associate it with the
    template and component.

 3. Model Binding: Use the formControlName directive in the view to bind an
    input to a specific form control.

    <form [formGroup]="myForm">
        <input formControlName="name" />
    </form>


    import { FormBuilder, FormGroup } from '@angular/forms';

    @Component({...})
    export class TwoWayBindingReactiveComponent {
        public myForm: FormGroup;

        constructor(private fb: FormBuilder) {
            this.myForm = this.fb.group({
                name: ['']
            });
        }
    }


This approach ensures synchronized data between the form input and the
FormControl associated with it.


BEST PRACTICES

 * Consistent Tracking: Whether through the FormsModule or ReactiveFormsModule,
   ensure consistent data tracking to avoid unexpected behavior.
 * Input Element Type: Not all elements support two-way binding. Use two-way
   bindings like [(ngModel)] with compatible input elements such as <input> and
   <textarea>.


WHEN TO USE TWO-WAY BINDING

While two-way binding can simplify form handling and updates in smaller
applications, its use in larger, complex applications might introduce
maintenance challenges and make it harder to understand data flow. In such
scenarios, one-way data flow using reactive patterns or unidirectional data flow
might be more suitable.

In Angular, creating, validating, and submitting forms can happen either using
Template-Driven Forms or Reactive Forms.


TEMPLATE-DRIVEN FORMS

Template-Driven Forms are easier to set up but offer limited functionality
compared to Reactive Forms.

STEPS TO USE TEMPLATE-DRIVEN FORMS

 1. Import the FormsModule: In the app module, you need to import FormsModule.

 2. Add a form tag: Within your component's markup, place a <form> tag that
    binds to NgForm.

 3. Bind to Form Controls: Use directives like ngModel to handle data bindings
    and validation.

 4. Customize Validation: Make use of built-in directives like required, or
    customize them like NgModel with ngControl.

 5. Work with Submission: Define a method for the ngSubmit event of the form.

TYPESCRIPT EXAMPLE: IMPLEMENTING TEMPLATE-DRIVEN FORMS

Here is the Angular typescript code:

import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'template-driven-form',
  template: `
    <form (ngSubmit)="onSubmit()" #userForm="ngForm">
      <input type="text" class="form-control" name="name" required ngModel>
      <button type="submit" [disabled]="userForm.invalid">Submit</button>
    </form>
  `
})
export class TemplateDrivenFormComponent {
  onSubmit() {
    // form submit logic
  }
}



REACTIVE FORMS

Reactive Forms offer more flexibility, allow you to define form controls in the
component class, can be easier to test and provide a clearer code structure.

STEPS TO USE REACTIVE FORMS

 1. Import the ReactiveFormsModule: In the app module, you need to import
    ReactiveFormsModule.

 2. Create the Form Controls Programmatically: In the component class, use the
    FormControl, FormGroup, and FormBuilder classes to create form controls.

 3. Bind to Form Controls: Use directives such as formControlName, or formGroup
    to link form controls to HTML elements.

 4. Customize Validation: Use Validators from @angular/forms, and create custom
    validators as needed.

 5. Work with Submission: Subscribe to the form's value or status changes, and
    perform actions accordingly, instead of using a method for ngSubmit as in
    Template-Driven forms.

TYPESCRIPT EXAMPLE: IMPLEMENTING REACTIVE FORMS

Here is the Angular typescript code:

import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormBuilder, Validators } from '@angular/forms';

@Component({
  selector: 'reactive-form',
  template: `
    <form [formGroup]="userForm" (ngSubmit)="onSubmit()">
      <input type="text" formControlName="name" class="form-control">
      <button type="submit" [disabled]="userForm.invalid">Submit</button>
    </form>
  `
})
export class ReactiveFormComponent {
  userForm = this.formBuilder.group({
    name: ['', Validators.required]
  });

  constructor(private formBuilder: FormBuilder) {}

  onSubmit() {
    // form submit logic
  }
}



CODE FOR APP MODULE

Here is the Angular typescript code for App Module:

import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

import { TemplateDrivenFormComponent } from './template-driven-form.component';
import { ReactiveFormComponent } from './reactive-form.component';

@NgModule({
  imports: [BrowserModule, ReactiveFormsModule],
  declarations: [TemplateDrivenFormComponent, ReactiveFormComponent],
  bootstrap: [TemplateDrivenFormComponent, ReactiveFormComponent]
})
export class AppModule {}

In Angular, you can make HTTP requests using Angular's built-in HttpClient
service. This is a more modern approach than the now deprecated HttpModule.


SETTING UP HTTPCLIENTMODULE

In your Angular module, import HttpClientModule and add it to the imports array.

import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClientModule } from '@angular/common/http';
import { AppComponent } from './app.component';

@NgModule({
  declarations: [AppComponent],  
  imports: [BrowserModule, HttpClientModule],  
  providers: [],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule {}



MAKING SIMPLE HTTP GET REQUEST

Here's an example of making a simple GET request to a REST API:

import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

@Injectable()
export class DataService {
  private apiURL = 'https://api.example.com/data';

  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  fetchData(): Observable<any> {
    return this.http.get<any>(this.apiURL);
  }
}



HANDLING RESPONSE

You can also handle the response using various HttpClient methods. Here are a
few examples:

GET METHOD WITH JSON RESPONSE

getData(): Observable<DataModel> {
  return this.http.get<DataModel>(this.apiURL);
}


GET METHOD FOR NON-JSON DATA

If you expect response data in a format other than JSON, HttpClient allows you
to specify the response type:

getTextData(): Observable<string> {
  return this.http.get(this.apiURL, { responseType: 'text' });
}


ERROR HANDLING

You can also handle errors using RxJS catchError operator. The HttpClient
methods such as get, post, etc., return an Observable that can be further
manipulated using RxJS operators.

Here is an example:

import { catchError, map } from 'rxjs/operators';
import { of } from 'rxjs';

getDataWithCatchError(): Observable<DataModel> {
  return this.http.get<DataModel>(this.apiURL).pipe(
    catchError((error) => {
      console.error('Error:', error);
      return of(null); // Return a default value or re-throw the error
    })
  );
}



MAKING OTHER HTTP REQUESTS

 * POST Request: Use post method. It allows you to send a request body.

   postData(data: any): Observable<any> {
     return this.http.post<any>(this.apiURL, data);
   }


 * PUT Request: Use put method for updating resources.

   updateData(data: any): Observable<any> {
     return this.http.put<any>(this.apiURL, data);
   }


 * DELETE Request: Use delete method for deleting resources.

   deleteData(id: string): Observable<any> {
     return this.http.delete<any>(`${this.apiURL}/${id}`);
   }


 * Custom Headers: You can pass an HttpHeaders object for custom headers.

   import { HttpHeaders } from '@angular/common/http';

   // Set up headers
   const headers = new HttpHeaders().set('Authorization', 'Bearer my-jwt-token');

   // Pass headers in the request
   return this.http.get<any>(this.apiURL, { headers });



SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS

For production-grade applications, it's important to secure your HTTP requests
over insecure networks (like the internet) using SSL/TLS.

Let's look at the different ways to pass data from a parent to a child component
in Angular.


TECHNIQUES FOR PARENT-TO-CHILD DATA FLOW

INTERPOLATION

 * Use: For simple textual or string-based data.

 * Parent Component: HTML: Provides data through interpolation.

   <app-child [dataProp]="'Hello from Parent!'"></app-child>


   * The dataProp attribute binds the literal string 'Hello from Parent!' to the
     child component.

 * Child Component: TypeScript: Receives data through @Input.

   @Input() dataProp: string;


PROPERTY BINDING

 * Use: For complex structured or dynamic data.

 * Parent Component: HTML: Binds data property.

   <app-child [dataProp]="parentData"></app-child>


   * Here, parentData is a property of the parent component.

 * Child Component: TypeScript: Receives data through @Input.

   @Input() dataProp: any;


   * Any changes to parentData will reflect in dataProp.

PASSING DATA TO CHILDREN: CODE EXAMPLE

Here is the Angular code:

The Parent Component's HTML:

<app-child [dataProp]="'Hello from Parent!'"></app-child>


The Parent Component's TypeScript:

export class ParentComponent {
  parentData = { message: 'Hello from Parent!' };
}


The Child Component's TypeScript:

import { Component, Input } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `<p>{{ dataProp.message }}</p>`
})
export class ChildComponent {
  @Input() dataProp: { message: string };
}

Angular's EventEmitter allows you to establish robust communication from a child
component to its parent component.


EVENTEMITTER IN ANGULAR

 * EventEmitter is an @Output property in Angular components.
 * It utilizes TypeScript generics to specify the data type of events being
   emitted.
 * Both EventEmitter and Output are imported from @angular/core.

Here is the Angular code:

import { Component, EventEmitter, Input, Output } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'child',
  template: '<button (click)="notifyParent()">Click me</button>',
})

export class ChildComponent {
  @Output() public customEvent: EventEmitter<string> = new EventEmitter<string>();
  @Input() public childProp: string;

  public notifyParent(): void {
    this.customEvent.emit(`Event emitted from child: ${this.childProp}`);
  }
}


In the parent component template, use the child component and listen to events:

@Component({
  selector: 'parent',
  template: ` <child [childProp]="parentProp" (customEvent)="handleCustomEvent($event)"></child>`,
})

export class ParentComponent {
  public parentProp: string = 'I am the parent!';
  public handleCustomEvent(eventData: string): void {
    console.log(`Received event in parent: ${eventData}`);
  }
}

Angular components undergo a series of lifecycle events, enabling design
patterns like lazy loading, data validation, and more.


CORE LIFECYCLE HOOKS

 * ngOnChanges: Triggers when the component receives input values from its
   parent.

 * ngOnInit: Initializes the component after its first ngOnChanges invocation.

 * ngDoCheck: Custom change detection mechanism.

 * ngAfterContentInit: Executed once the component's content projection (if any)
   is complete.

 * ngAfterContentChecked: Checks the component's projected content each time
   it's validated.

 * ngAfterViewInit: Serves as a callback for when a component's view and its
   children are constructed.

 * ngAfterViewChecked: Triggers each time the view and its children undergo
   change detection.

 * ngOnDestroy: Invoked just before the component is destroyed, clearing any
   long-lived resources.


CODE EXAMPLE: LIFECYCLE HOOKS

Here is the Angular code:

import { Component, Input } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-lifecycle-hooks',
  template: '<i>{{ message }}</i>'
})
export class LifecycleHooksComponent {
  @Input() message: string;

  ngOnChanges(): void {
    console.log('ngOnChanges triggered.');
  }

  ngOnInit(): void {
    console.log('ngOnInit triggered.');
  }

  ngDoCheck(): void {
    console.log('ngDoCheck triggered.');
  }

  ngAfterContentInit(): void {
    console.log('ngAfterContentInit triggered.');
  }

  ngAfterContentChecked(): void {
    console.log('ngAfterContentChecked triggered.');
  }

  ngAfterViewInit(): void {
    console.log('ngAfterViewInit triggered.');
  }

  ngAfterViewChecked(): void {
    console.log('ngAfterViewChecked triggered.');
  }

  ngOnDestroy(): void {
    console.log('ngOnDestroy triggered.');
  }
}

To create a custom structural directive in Angular, follow these steps:

 1. Implement the Directive decorator
 2. Define a Directive class and extend from NgTemplateOutlet or implement the
    TemplateRef interface
 3. Handle Input Variables to adapt the directive to different contexts
 4. Use the Renderer2 for dynamic DOM manipulation
 5. Implement the ngOnChanges method for handling input changes
 6. Link the Directive in your module


CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM STRUCTURAL DIRECTIVE

Here is the TypeScript code:

import { Directive, Input, TemplateRef, ViewContainerRef } from '@angular/core';

@Directive({
selector: '[appUnless]'
})
export class UnlessDirective {
@Input() set appUnless(condition: boolean) {
  if (!condition) {
    this.vcRef.createEmbeddedView(this.templateRef);
  } else {
    this.vcRef.clear();
  }
}

constructor(
  private templateRef: TemplateRef<any>,
  private vcRef: ViewContainerRef
) { }
}



IN A NUTSHELL

By extending NgTemplateOutlet or implementing TemplateRef, you gain access to
the directive's host view.

You then use the @Input property with an accompanying setter to monitor the host
context and decide whether to render its associated template.

By incorporating the ViewContainerRef for the host view and TemplateRef for the
associated template, the directive effectively controls the rendering of a
section of the DOM tree based on predefined conditions.

Remember:

 * Directives are your go-to for DOM manipulation and creating dynamic
   templates.
 * Structural directives, in particular, enable you to introduce or remove
   elements within the DOM.

Observables can make your Angular app more responsive and efficient. When
integrated with services, they provide a streamlined way to communicate data
between various components.


CORE COMPONENTS

 * Service: Acts as a central data hub, managing state and data queries.
 * Component: Subscribes to the service's observable to receive data updates.


OBSERVABLE-BASED WORKFLOW

 1. Data Setup: The service identifies the data source and wraps it in an
    Observable. Data changes are broadcast using the Observable's next() method.
 2. Data Consumption: Components subscribe to the service's Observable to
    receive data updates. The Observer's next method triggers the associated
    logic in each component.


REAL-TIME APPLICATION

 * Chat Applications: To communicate real-time messages across components and
   refresh UI accordingly.
 * Stock Monitoring Apps: To provide real-time data updates on stock prices and
   analysis charts.
 * Content Collaboration Tools: For multiple users to view and interact with
   documents and changes in real time.


ANGULAR CODE EXAMPLES

Here is the TypeScript code:

SERVICE (DATA PRODUCER)

import { Observable, Subject } from 'rxjs';

export class DataService {
  private data: string[] = ['Initial data'];
  private dataSubject: Subject<string[]> = new Subject<string[]>();

  // Method returning the Observable for data changes
  getDataObservable(): Observable<string[]> {
    return this.dataSubject.asObservable();
  }

  // Method triggering data change updates
  updateData(newData: string) {
    this.data.push(newData);
    this.dataSubject.next(this.data);
  }
}


COMPONENT (DATA CONSUMER)

@Component({
  selector: 'app-example',
  template: '<div *ngFor="let item of dataArray">{{ item }}</div>'
})
export class ExampleComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  dataArray: string[] = [];
  dataSubscription: Subscription;

  constructor(private dataService: DataService) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.dataSubscription = this.dataService.getDataObservable().subscribe(updatedData => {
      this.dataArray = updatedData;
    });
  }

  ngOnDestroy() {
    // Clean up the subscription to avoid memory leaks
    this.dataSubscription.unsubscribe();
  }
}

Let's look at several \textit{Service Provider Types} in Angular, as they relate
to dependency injection and Angular modules.


THE SERVICE PROVIDER

The Service Provider is responsible for creating the actual service at the point
of use. Angular offers five main provider types:

 1. Root (@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })): A single instance is shared
    across the entire Angular application.

 2. Module (@Injectable({ providedIn: 'any' })): A single instance is shared
    within the entirety of the parent module (or any module for "any").

 3. Platform (@Injectable({ providedIn: 'platform' })): The provider is
    instantiated when an Angular platform is created and lives for the duration
    of the app.

 4. @Component (@Injectable({ providedIn: MyComponent })): Instantiated for a
    given component and all of its children.

 5. Custom Provider Scope: These providers are instantiated per a custom Angular
    injector (you can define a custom injector and register the provider with
    it).


WHEN TO USE EACH PROVIDER TYPE

 * Root: Ideal for services that are shared throughout the app, such as logging
   or user authentication.

 * Module: Best suited for providing a service that is specific to the parent
   module, ensuring that it's not accessible everywhere in the app.

 * Platform: Used for service providers that need a unique instance for the
   entire application. Examples include services providing application-wide
   configuration and state.

 * @Component: Effective when a service is scoped to a particular component and
   any of its child components.

 * Custom Provider Scope: These are tailored for specific requirements where
   none of the standard provider types provide a perfect fit.


BEST PRACTICES

MINIMIZE GLOBAL STATE

Though it's appropriate to use the Root provider type for certain services like
authentication, favor more scoped providers to minimize global state and improve
app maintainability.

SERVICE-LAZY LOADING

Leverage module-provided services for feature modules to promote lazy loading
and enhance app performance.

FLEXIBLE CONFIGURATION

You can customize a service's provider using a configuration object. Angular's
forRoot() and forChild() methods allow tailored setup for a service within the
application or specific modules.

DYNAMIC PROVIDER MANAGEMENT

Angular provides APIs for \textit{dynamic loading} and \textit{provider tree}
manipulations. This supports scenarios where providers need to be registered at
runtime.

CONSIDER GLOBAL SERVICES FOR GLOBAL CONCERNS

Certain core functionalities like logging and global HTTP interceptors make
sense as global services.


CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM PROVIDER SCOPE

Here is the Angular TypeScript Code:

import { InjectionToken, Injectable, Injector } from '@angular/core';

// Define a token
export const MyToken = new InjectionToken<string>('MyToken');

// Create a service
@Injectable()
export class MyService {
  constructor() {
    console.log('MyService instantiated.');
  }
}

// Create a custom injector
const customInjector = Injector.create({
  providers: [
    { provide: MyToken, useValue: 'Custom Provider' },
    { provide: MyService, useClass: MyService, deps: [] },
  ],
});

// Use the built-in injector for the root module
// You can also add this provider in the providers array of the root module
@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root',
  useFactory: () => customInjector.get(MyService),
})
export class MyServiceCustomProvider {
  constructor(private myService: MyService) {
    console.log('MyServiceCustomProvider instantiated.');
    console.log('Injected MyService:', myService);
  }
}

The HttpClient module empowers Angular applications to send and receive JSON
data sets with back-end data through an assortment of HTTP requests, including
GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE.

Let's have a look at how to deal with JSON response data after making an HTTP
call, focusing on code snippets.


HTTP CALL TO FETCH JSON DATA

 1. To start, create a JSON file with an array of dummy data.

 2. Next, import HttpClientModule to AppModule and inject HttpClient into the
    relevant service or component.

 3. Then, create a local JSON file to emulate a server call:

    * countries.json:

    [
        {
            "id": "1",
            "name": "USA"
        },
        {
            "id": "2",
            "name": "India"
        }
    ]


 4. Define the service method to fetch the data:

    * country.service.ts:

    import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
    import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';
    import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

    @Injectable({
      providedIn: 'root'
    })
    export class CountryService {
      private countriesUrl = '/assets/countries.json';

      constructor(private http: HttpClient) { }

      getCountries(): Observable<Country[]> {
        return this.http.get<Country[]>(this.countriesUrl);
      }
    }


Here the Country can be a TypeScript interface:

   export interface Country {
       id: string;
       name: string;
   }


 5. Finally, subscribe in the component to process the response:

    * country.component.ts:

    import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
    import { CountryService, Country } from './country.service';

    @Component({
      // Template and other metadata
    })
    export class CountryComponent implements OnInit {
      countries: Country[] = [];

      constructor(private countryService: CountryService) {}

      ngOnInit() {
        this.countryService.getCountries().subscribe(data => {
          this.countries = data;
        });
      }
    }



TESTING THE SERVICE METHOD

Test the getCountries method to verify its response:

 * country.service.spec.ts:


import { TestBed, inject, async } from '@angular/core/testing';
import { HttpClientTestingModule, HttpTestingController } from '@angular/common/http/testing';

import { CountryService } from './country.service';

describe('CountryService', () => {
  let countryService: CountryService;
  let httpMock: HttpTestingController;

  beforeEach(() => {
    TestBed.configureTestingModule({
      imports: [HttpClientTestingModule],
      providers: [CountryService]
    });
  });

  beforeEach(inject([CountryService, HttpTestingController],
    (service: CountryService, controller: HttpTestingController) => {
      countryService = service;
      httpMock = controller;
  }));

  it('should retrieve countries from the API', () => {
    const mockCountries = [
      { id: '1', name: 'USA' },
      { id: '2', name: 'India' }
    ];

    countryService.getCountries().subscribe(countries => {
      expect(countries.length).toBe(2);
      expect(countries).toEqual(mockCountries);
    });

    const request = httpMock.expectOne('/assets/countries.json');
    expect(request.request.method).toBe('GET');
    request.flush(mockCountries);
  });
});



Alternatively, you can also manually manage the HTTP request expectations and
responses:

 * country.spec.ts:

it('should retrieve countries from the API', () => {
  const mockCountries = [
    { id: '1', name: 'USA' },
    { id: '2', name: 'India' }
  ];

  const request = httpMock.expectOne('/assets/countries.json');
  request.flush(mockCountries);

  countryService.getCountries().subscribe(countries => {
    expect(countries.length).toBe(2);
    expect(countries).toEqual(mockCountries);
  });
});


This way, you ensure your app's frontend data processing accurately matches the
backend.


KEY POINTS:

 * The HttpClient API provides a get method for fetching data.
 * A single component can subscribe to the same observable multiple times,
   potentially causing multiple HTTP requests.
 * To prevent this, return the Observable from the service method and invoke
   http.get() just once.


FURTHER TIPS:

 * Be Consistent: Use observables throughout your application for more unified
   and clean code.
 * Error Handling: Don't forget to incorporate a proper error handling mechanism
   inside your subscribe method.


SUMMARY

Using the HttpClient module in Angular assists with executing various HTTP
requests, including fetching JSON data. The approach involves invoking the get
method and subscribing to the returned Observable to process server data on the
client side. Subsequent code can take advantage of this JSON to meet specific
application requirements.

When it comes to dealing with RESTful APIs and error handling in Angular, the
HttpClient and services play a pivotal role.


ANGULAR'S HTTPCLIENT

Angular's HttpClient is an efficient way to send requests and handle responses.
It simplifies working with RESTful APIs, providing methods to handle HTTP
operations such as GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, and more.

MAKING THE HTTP REQUEST

The HttpClient service offers a cohesive API for defining the request type,
setting headers, passing data, and handling the response.

Here's a simplified example:

import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';

export class DataService {
  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getData() {
    return this.http.get<any[]>('api/data');
  }
}


ERROR HANDLING

Angular's HttpClient also offers error handling. You can use methods like
catchError or pipe along with RxJS features such as throwError to manage
potential errors.

Here's an example of a service with error handling:

import { HttpClient, HttpErrorResponse } from '@angular/common/http';
import { catchError } from 'rxjs/operators';
import { throwError } from 'rxjs';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root',
})
export class DataService {
  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getData() {
    return this.http.get<any[]>('api/data').pipe(
      catchError(this.handleError)
    );
  }

  private handleError(error: HttpErrorResponse) {
    if (error.error instanceof ErrorEvent) {
      console.error('An error occurred:', error.error.message);
    } else {
      console.error(`Backend returned code ${error.status}, body was: ${error.error}`);
    }
    return throwError('Something bad happened; please try again later.');
  }
}



BEST PRACTICES

 1. Centralizing Configuration: It's best to centralize the configuration of
    your API endpoints and headers, perhaps using an environment file or a
    dedicated configuration service.
 2. Use HTTP Interceptors: Interceptors provide a convenient way to modify
    requests and responses across your application. They can be especially
    useful for adding common headers, handling tokens, and even globally
    managing errors. Some IDEs list all the available services that you can
    inject in the constructor. If it's not automatically populated, you can
    import the Request and Response services or access them from the
    @nestjs/common package.
 3. Leverage Services for Data Management: Separate concerns by using services
    to manage data, keeping your components lean and focused. This is a best
    practice in Angular for data retrieval.


RECOMMENDATIONS FOR ERROR HANDLING

 * Handle Errors within the Service: This prevents leaking implementation
   details to the component.
 * Standardize Error Responses: If your API can send a standard error object,
   your service can operate more consistently in its error handling, leading to
   a more predictable and manageable client-side experience.

When it comes to error handling in Angular services, there are a few best
practices to keep in mind.

Treat HTTP calls as cold observables: This means actions like subscribe are
necessary for the call to take place. This design allows for precise control
over error handling and multiple subscriptions to the same observable.

IMPLEMENTING ERROR HANDLING IN SERVICES

Here is the best practice for the code:

 * Service: The ApiService acts as a central place for all API-related
   activities, providing consistent error handling and data transformation.
 * Component: The DataComponent remains focused on UI interactions, with the
   error case being just one more possible outcome from the ApiService. This
   keeps the component code cleaner and easier to test.

Service Code: Below is the TypeScript and Angular-specific code:

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient, HttpErrorResponse } from '@angular/common/http';
import { Observable, throwError } from 'rxjs';
import { catchError } from 'rxjs/operators';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class ApiService {
  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getData(url: string): Observable<any> {
    return this.http.get<any>(url).pipe(
      catchError(this.handleError)
    );
  }

  private handleError(error: HttpErrorResponse): Observable<never> {
    let errorMessage = 'Unknown error!';
    if (error.status === 404) {
      errorMessage = 'Resource not found.';
    }
    return throwError(errorMessage);
  }
}


Component Code: Below is the TypeScript and Angular-specific code:

import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { ApiService } from './api.service';

@Component({...})
export class DataComponent {
  data: any[];
  error: string;

  constructor(private apiService: ApiService) {}

  loadData(url: string): void {
    this.apiService.getData(url).subscribe({
      next: (data) => this.data = data,
      error: (err) => this.error = err
    });
  }
}

Route Guards allow you to control the navigation process in Angular based on
specific conditions, providing enhanced security and user experience. They are
classified into three types, each serving a unique purpose:

 * CanActivate: Ensures navigation can begin.
 * CanDeactivate: Confirms if a user can exit the current route.
 * Resolve: Resolves data to be loaded before route activation.


CODE EXAMPLE: ROUTE CONFIGURATION

Here is a simplified version:

import { Routes, RouterModule } from '@angular/router';
import { CanActivateGuard } from './can-activate.guard';
import { CanDeactivateGuard } from './can-deactivate.guard';
import { ResolveGuard } from './resolve.guard';
import { MyComponent } from './my-component';

const routes: Routes = [
  {
    path: 'protected',
    component: MyComponent,
    canActivate: [CanActivateGuard],
    canDeactivate: [CanDeactivateGuard],
    resolve: { data: ResolveGuard }
  }
];


In the app-routing.module.ts, add:

@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes)],
  exports: [RouterModule],
  providers: [CanActivateGuard, CanDeactivateGuard, ResolveGuard],
})
export class AppRoutingModule {}



CODE EXAMPLE: GUARD IMPLEMENTATIONS

CANACTIVATE GUARD

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { CanActivate, ActivatedRouteSnapshot, RouterStateSnapshot, Router } from '@angular/router';
import { AuthService } from './auth.service';

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CanActivateGuard implements CanActivate {
  constructor(private authService: AuthService, private router: Router) {}

  canActivate(route: ActivatedRouteSnapshot, state: RouterStateSnapshot): boolean {
    if (!this.authService.isLoggedIn) {
      this.router.navigate(['/login']);
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  }
}


CANDEACTIVATE GUARD

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { CanDeactivate } from '@angular/router';
import { MyComponent } from './my-component';

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CanDeactivateGuard implements CanDeactivate<MyComponent> {
  canDeactivate(component: MyComponent): boolean {
    if (component.form.dirty) {
      return confirm('Do you really want to discard the changes?');
    }
    return true;
  }
}


RESOLVE GUARD

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { ActivatedRouteSnapshot, Resolve, RouterStateSnapshot } from '@angular/router';
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { DataService } from './data.service';

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ResolveGuard implements Resolve<DataType> {
  constructor(private dataService: DataService) {}

  resolve(route: ActivatedRouteSnapshot, state: RouterStateSnapshot): Observable<DataType> {
    return this.dataService.getData();
  }
}

In the Angular framework, route parameters represents dynamic segments of the
URL. You can extract these dynamic values to customize your components or tailor
data requests, making your application more versatile.

ACCESSING ROUTE PARAMETERS

 1. ActivatedRoute Snapshot: You can use this.route.snapshot to fetch route
    parameters synchronously inside the ngOnInit lifecycle hook. This method is
    quick but not suitable for data that may change without the component being
    destroyed.

 2. Observable: For dynamic data, such as in server requests, use
    this.route.params.subscribe(params => { /* access params here */ }). This
    way, the component can respond to parameter changes in real time.

CODE EXAMPLE: READING ROUTE PARAMETERS

Here is the Angular Component:

import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
import { ActivatedRoute } from '@angular/router';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-my-component',
  template: '<p>Data: {{ id }}</p>'
})
export class MyComponent implements OnInit {
  id: string;

  constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    // Synchronous read with snapshot
    this.id = this.route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id');

    // Asynchronous read with Observable
    this.route.params.subscribe(params => {
      this.id = params['id'];
    });
  }
}

Route data preloading is a strategy that enhances the user experience by
preparing data or performing tasks in advance of a route being activated.


PRELOADING STRATEGIES

 * No Preloading: Standard behavior, routes are loaded when activated.
 * Preloading: Immediate but non-blocking loading.
 * Lazy Loading: Routes are loaded on-demand.

Angular's PreloadingStrategy allows you to define custom preloaders.

Here's the step-by-step guide to creating a custom preloading strategy:

 1. Define Preloading Strategy
 2. Implement Strategy
 3. Configure Preloading


CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM PRELOADING STRATEGY

Here is the Angular TypeScript code:

 * The file app-preloading-strategy.ts contains the custom AppPreloadingStrategy
   class.

   import { PreloadingStrategy, Route } from '@angular/router';
   import { Observable, of } from 'rxjs';

   export class AppPreloadingStrategy implements PreloadingStrategy {
     preload(route: Route, load: () => Observable<any>): Observable<any> {
       return route.data && route.data.preload ? load() : of(null);
     }
   }


 * In app-routing.module.ts, use the created strategy.

   const routes: Routes = [
     { path: '...', loadChildren: '...', data: { preload: true } }
   ];

   @NgModule({
     imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes, { preloadingStrategy: AppPreloadingStrategy })],
     exports: [RouterModule]
   })
   export class AppRoutingModule { }

In Reactive Forms, dynamic management of form controls brings adaptability to
multi-step forms and user interaction. You can add, move, and remove form
controls as needed, catering to users' context-specific requirements.


KEY CONCEPTS

 * FormArray: Used to handle dynamic form control lists (FormGroup instances).
 * FormBuilder: Simplifies form setup and dynamic control management.


CORE DIRECTIVES & METHODS

 * formArrayName: Establishes binding between the template and FormArray.
 * form-controls: Directive to manage the addition and removal of controls.
 * get, push, removeAt: FormArray methods catering to control retrieval,
   addition, and removal.


IMPLEMENT DYNAMIC CONTROL MANAGEMENT

1. DEFINE YOUR FORMGROUP AND FORMARRAY

Set up your main form group, embedding a FormArray for dynamic control
management.

import { FormBuilder, FormGroup, FormArray } from '@angular/forms';

export class MyFormComponent {
  mainForm: FormGroup;

  constructor(private fb: FormBuilder) {
    this.mainForm = this.fb.group({
      dynamicControls: this.fb.array([]) // This is the FormArray
    });
  }
}


2. ASSOCIATE FORMARRAY WITH TEMPLATE

Use formArrayName in your template to connect the FormArray with the UI.

<form [formGroup]="mainForm">
  <div formArrayName="dynamicControls">
      <div *ngFor="let control of dynamicControls.controls; let i = index">
        <input [formControlName]="i">
        <button (click)="removeControl(i)">Remove</button>
      </div>
    <button (click)="addControl()">Add Control</button>
  </div>
</form>


3. HANDLE CONTROL ACTIONS

Define methods in your component to handle the addition and removal of form
controls.

  // In your MyFormComponent class
  get dynamicControls() {
    return this.mainForm.get('dynamicControls') as FormArray;
  }

  addControl() {
    const control = this.fb.control(''); // Or a FormGroup if the control is a group
    this.dynamicControls.push(control);
  }

  removeControl(index: number) {
    this.dynamicControls.removeAt(index);
  }



BEST PRACTICES

 * Separate Template and Component Logic: Keep form control management in the
   component class, promoting a clear separation of concerns.
 * Validate Dynamically Added Controls: Don't forget to include any necessary
   validations for newly added controls to maintain data integrity.

Form groups are a pivotal feature of Angular's form-handling capabilities. They
allow for arranging form controls, segregation into logical units, and
implementing modular form validation. By using form groups, you get a
well-organized, and more manageable structure for your form controls.

Here are the key components of form groups:

 1. Parent-Child Relationships: A form group can have descendant form groups as
    well as form controls as its "children". This logical hierarchy accurately
    models real-world form structures.

 2. Validation Completeness: Form groups enforce validation only when all their
    child controls and groups are also valid. This ensures comprehensive
    validation across related fields.

 3. Form Values: A form group's value mirrors the structure of its child
    controls, providing a consistent and predictable way to access form data.


CODE EXAMPLE: FORM GROUP

Here is the Angular Code:

app.module.ts

import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';
import { AppComponent } from './app.component';

@NgModule({
  declarations: [AppComponent],
  imports: [BrowserModule, ReactiveFormsModule],
