Code splitting in Angular is a technique that's used to reduce initial bundle
size, thereby improving app load time. Angular offers various strategies for
effective code splitting.


STRATEGIES IN ANGULAR

1. LAZY LOADING

Angular modules can be set up for lazy loading, delaying their loading until
they are needed. This is especially useful for large, feature-rich applications.

Instead of:

import { FeatureModule } from './feature/feature.module';


Use this:

const routes: Routes = [
  { 
    path: 'feature', 
    loadChildren: './feature/feature.module#FeatureModule' 
  }
];


Or even better, use the dynamic import() syntax:

const routes: Routes = [
  { 
    path: 'feature', 
    loadChildren: () => import('./feature/feature.module').then(m => m.FeatureModule) 
  }
];


2. PRELOADING STRATEGIES

To give users a feel of snappy navigation while ensuring modules are loaded in
the background, Angular supports different preloading strategies:

 * NoPreloading: Modules load only when requested.
 * PreloadAllModules: All lazy modules are loaded immediately after the app
   loads.
 * Custom strategies: For a nuanced approach to preloading, you can define a
   custom PreloadingStrategy service that specifies which modules to preload.

To use a preloading strategy such as PreloadAllModules, update your main routing
module:

@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes, { preloadingStrategy: PreloadAllModules })],
  exports: [RouterModule]
})
export class AppRoutingModule {}


3. DYNAMIC COMPONENT RENDERING

You can also leverage dynamic component rendering to load components and their
associated modules on demand. This is useful when dealing with components that
are not always required.

Use the ComponentFactoryResolver in combination with Angular's view container to
achieve this.

When rendering a component:

const componentFactory = this.componentFactoryResolver.resolveComponentFactory(YourComponent);
const viewContainerRef = this.yourViewContainerRef;
viewContainerRef.clear();
const componentRef = viewContainerRef.createComponent(componentFactory);



CONFIGURATION

In general, it's good practice to be mindful of your application requirements
and only split code when necessary. It can lead to excessive network requests,
negatively impacting the initial load.

Tools like Angular CLI, offer out-of-the-box support for code splitting.

Here's a basic setup example:

 * Install the @angular-devkit/build-angular NPM package if you don't have it.

 * In the angular.json configuration file, ensure that the "budgets" section has
   appropriate settings to manage bundle sizes.

   "budgets": [
     {
       "type": "initial",
       "maximumWarning": "2mb"
     },
     // Additional configurations
   ]


   Also, remember to set "outputHashing": "all" to ensure that filenames change
   after every build.

 * Trigger production builds with:

   ng build --prod


This sets the stage for code-splitting and bundle optimization.

Here are practical security best practices tailored for Angular applications:


CORS CONFIGURATION

Angular apps often interface with diverse services and may introduce
Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) concerns. Ensure backend APIs are correctly
configured to whitelist known, trusted origins and eliminate unrestricted CORS
rules.

